def datacreate(df): ## creating x,y variables based on the fitted data 
    x = []
    y = []
    for i in range(50, df.shape[0]):
        x.append(df[i-50:i, 0])
        y.append(df[i, 0])
    x = np.array(x)
    y = np.array(y)
    return x,y

x_train, y_train = datacreate(data_train)
x_test, y_test = datacreate(data_test)

df = pd.DataFrame(data,columns = ['date','close'])
df.date = pd.to_datetime(df.date)
df = df.set_index("date")
df.head()
train, test = df[:-12], df[-12:]

scaler = MinMaxScaler()
train = scaler.fit_transform(train)
test = scaler.fit_transform(test)
test
## the process is very similar to what has been happening in the past except the use of the generator

n_input = 12 
n_features = 1

#given we locked date as an index this time, the data is presented in a time series manner which enables us to use the timeseriesgenerator
generator = TimeseriesGenerator(train, train, length = n_input, batch_size = 6) 

model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(200, activation= 'relu', input_shape=(n_input, n_features)))
model.add(Dropout(0.15))
model.add(Dense(1))
model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss= 'mse')

model.fit_generator(generator, epochs = 180)

predictions = []

batch = train[-n_input:].reshape((1,n_input,n_features))

for i in range(n_input):
    predictions.append(model.predict(batch)[0]) ## appending predictions to predictions list
    batch = np.append(batch[:, 1:,:], [[predictions[i]]], axis=1)
